.TH JOURNALD-ARCHIVE 8 "2026-06-08" "journald-archive 0.3.1" "System Administration"
.SH NAME
journald-archive \- move rotated systemd journals to a compressed archive
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B journald-archive
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B journald-archive
implements a tiered storage scheme for systemd-journald logs.
It moves rotated, sealed journal files out of the hot tier
.RI ( /var/log/journal/ )
into a compressed btrfs archive
.RI ( /var/log/journal_archive/ ),
keeping the hot tier small so that ordinary
.BR journalctl (1)
queries stay fast.
.PP
On each invocation it:
.IP \(bu 3
verifies that the archive mount point is an actual mount point and aborts
otherwise (to avoid filling the root filesystem);
.IP \(bu 3
if the archive has less than
.B FREE_MARGIN_MIB
free, deletes the oldest archived journals until that much space is available
again, so incoming files have room (see
.BR FREE_MARGIN_MIB );
.IP \(bu 3
moves every rotated
.RI ( *@*.journal )
file older than the configured grace period (see
.BR GRACE_MINUTES )
from the active machine's journal directory into
the corresponding directory under the archive (a cross-filesystem move, which
recompresses the data via the archive's
.B compress\-force=zstd
mount option).
.PP
Active (currently written) journal files are never touched. The grace period
both avoids racing journald during rotation and keeps the most recently
rotated logs in the fast hot tier.
.PP
Retention is governed by physical disk space, not by a fixed time or logical
size: the archive keeps as much history as fits in its loopback file, so better
compression automatically yields more retained history. There is consequently
no guaranteed minimum retention period \(em under a fixed disk budget a burst of
logs can always push the oldest history out. Size the loopback file to bound
retention by disk.
.PP
.B journald-archive
takes no arguments and is normally invoked by
.BR journald-archive.timer (5)
every 30 minutes, not run by hand.
.SH CONFIGURATION
Runtime configuration is read from
.IR /etc/default/journald-archive .
The following variables are recognised:
.TP
.B ARCHIVE_MOUNT
Mount point of the compressed archive. Default
.IR /var/log/journal_archive .
.TP
.B ARCHIVE_FILE
Backing btrfs loopback file. Default
.IR /var/log/journal_archive.btrfs .
.TP
.B FREE_MARGIN_MIB
Free space, in MiB, to keep available in the archive. When free space falls
below this, the oldest archived journals are deleted until it is restored,
making room for incoming files. Defaults to about 1/16 of the archive size when
unset. Raise it if journald's
.B SystemMaxFileSize
is large, so that a single rotated journal always fits; it is capped at half the
archive to keep a misconfigured value from emptying it.
.TP
.B GRACE_MINUTES
Minimum age, in minutes, before a rotated journal is moved to the archive.
Larger values keep more recent history in the fast hot tier (queryable with
plain
.BR journalctl );
it also avoids racing journald right after rotation. Defaults to 30 when
unset, matching the timer interval. Examples: 60 (one hour), 1440 (one day).
.PP
The file is re-read on every invocation, so changes take effect on the next
timer tick without a daemon reload.
.SH EXIT STATUS
Exits zero on success, including when there is nothing to move. Exits non-zero
if the archive mount point is not mounted or a fatal error occurs.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /usr/lib/journald-archive/journald-archive
The script itself. It is a private helper invoked by the timer and is
deliberately not placed on
.BR $PATH .
.TP
.I /etc/default/journald-archive
Runtime configuration.
.TP
.I /var/log/journal_archive.btrfs
Compressed btrfs loopback backing the archive.
.TP
.I /var/log/journal_archive/
Archive mount point (cold tier).
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR journalctl (1),
.BR systemd-journald.service (8),
.BR journald.conf (5),
.BR mergerfs (1)
